        <body>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <head type="title">&#x201C;Shagram’s Farewell to Shetland&#x201D;</head>
                <!--An apparatus may contain all or only some of the following sections.-->
                <div type="section" xml:id="TITLE">
                    <head type="section">Title</head>
                    <p>Title written “SHAGRAMS FAREWELL TO SHETLAND.” </p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="GENRE">
                    <head type="section">Genre</head>
                    <p>Body paragraph.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="MAJORMS">
                    <head type="section">Manuscripts</head>
                    <p>MS V.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DATE">
                    <head type="section">Date</head>
                    <p> <date when="1829-10-18">18 October 1829</date>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="COMPPUB">
                    <head type="section">Composition &#x0026; Publication</head>
                    <p>Printed PJR, 1:28-29; Works, 2:276-77.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DISCUSSION">
                    <head type="section">Discussion</head>
                    <p>The poem refers to a real pony, kept in the stable at the far end of the <placeName type="building" corresp="#HERNE">Herne Hill garden</placeName>. 
                        (see Ruskin’s Camberwell, 10). As Collingwood notes (PJR, 1:273), 
                        Ruskin named his pony after the one in The Monastery that balks at crossing the bog 
                        and that detects the presence of the <persName type="fictional" corresp="#WHITELADY">White Lady</persName>.</p>
                    
                    <p>The poem’s lament by <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>’s pony for his native <placeName corresp="#SCOTLAND">Scotland</placeName> 
                        was doubtless inspired by an October 18 evening lecture on cruelty to animals, 
                        delivered by Reverend Edward Andrews, Ruskin’s tutor (for the lecture, see RFL, 203, 204 n. 1).</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="TEXTUALNOTE">
                    <head type="section">Textual Note</head>
                    <p>Body paragraph.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
